I.
Here is how you run a futures exchange:
=09You offer some bets on some propositions, say, whether Bitcoin will go u=
p or down.=09Some people come and take the long side of the bet (betting th=
at Bitcoin will go up)=C2=A0and others take the short side (betting that it=
 will go down).=09In a sense, they are betting against each other, but they=
 never meet and are not betting against each other directly. Instead,=C2=A0=
you=C2=A0=E2=80=94 the exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0are on the other side of all=
 of their bets. You pay out the winners and collect from the losers. They a=
ll take your credit, not each other=E2=80=99s. The point of the exchange is=
 to be a trustworthy central counterparty for all the bets.=09They all have=
 to start by depositing some money in their accounts, so you can be confide=
nt they=E2=80=99ll pay up on the bets. Let=E2=80=99s say the deposit is $2,=
000 per Bitcoin bet, long or short.
  [1]
 This is called =E2=80=9Cinitial margin.=E2=80=9D=09Each day,
  [2]
=C2=A0you check if Bitcoin went up or down.=09If it went up, you take some =
money out of the accounts of the short bettors and put it into the accounts=
 of the long bettors.
  [3]

=09If it went down, you take some money out of the accounts of the long bet=
tors and put it into the accounts of the short bettors.=09If a bettor=E2=80=
=99s account gets too low (because Bitcoin has moved against her), say belo=
w $1,000, you call her up and ask her to deposit more money.
  [4]
=C2=A0This is called =E2=80=9Cvariation margin.=E2=80=9D If she doesn=E2=80=
=99t do it, you close out her bet at a loss.=09If a bettor=E2=80=99s accoun=
t gets really high (because Bitcoin has moved in her favor), she can withdr=
aw some of the money in her account. If I bet on Bitcoin when it is at $17,=
000, depositing $2,000 of initial margin, and it goes up to $30,000, then I=
 have $15,000 in my account. (My initial $2,000 plus $13,000 of market move=
s.) You might let me withdraw, say, $12,000 of it, leaving $3,000 in the ac=
count in case Bitcoin falls again.=09If a bettor=E2=80=99s account ever get=
s=C2=A0below=C2=A0zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0if Bitcoin has moved so far against h=
er so quickly that you didn=E2=80=99t have time to ask for more money or cl=
ose out her bet, and now she owes more on the bet than she has in her accou=
nt =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that=E2=80=99s bad. You still have to pay out the wi=
nner on the bet, but you can=E2=80=99t collect from the loser. (You can cal=
l and ask her for more money, but she might have made herself scarce.)=C2=
=A0You have to pay the winner out of your own =E2=80=94=C2=A0the exchange=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0money. If you don=E2=80=99t have enough money, th=
en that=E2=80=99s really bad. Then you can=E2=80=99t pay out all your custo=
mers on the amounts in their accounts.

I want to make a few points about this model. First, it is really common an=
d traditional. There are lots of futures exchanges; we have, for reasons,  =
 talked a   lot this year about the London Metals Exchange, and the above d=
escription basically covers the LME if you substitute =E2=80=9Cnickel=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Caluminum=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9CBitcoin.=E2=80=9D
Second, notice that in this model there are no Bitcoins at all. Some of you=
r customers are long Bitcoin and some are short Bitcoin but you, the exchan=
ge, never have to have any Bitcoins. There are no Bitcoins in the customers=
=E2=80=99 accounts, or in yours. You just sit in the middle of some bets be=
tween the customers. You hold onto some money for them =E2=80=94=C2=A0the a=
mount they deposited as collateral for their bets, customarily called =E2=
=80=9Cmargin=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you don=E2=80=99t keep the underly=
ing=C2=A0thing, the Bitcoin that they are betting on, in a safe.
  [5]
=C2=A0You can trade nickel futures on the London Metals Exchange, but the L=
ME does not own any nickel.
  [6]
=C2=A0
Third, this model is at its core about offering=C2=A0leveraged=C2=A0trading=
 on Bitcoins: It=E2=80=99s a way for people to bet on Bitcoin going up with=
out paying the full $17,000-ish that you=E2=80=99d need to buy a Bitcoin, s=
ince they only have to put up $2,000 of margin in Step 4, which=C2=A0is les=
s than $17,000. And it=E2=80=99s a way for people to bet on Bitcoin going d=
own, which is a necessarily leveraged trade: To bet against Bitcoin, you ei=
ther need to borrow a Bitcoin and sell it or do a futures trade; there is n=
o simple unlevered way to just hold negative one Bitcoin.
And so this model generalizes to doing margin trading on the actual underly=
ing asset. Instead of saying =E2=80=9Cdeposit $2,000 to bet on Bitcoin usin=
g futures,=E2=80=9D you could say =E2=80=9Cdeposit $2,000 and=C2=A0we=E2=80=
=99ll lend you the other $15,000 to buy a Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D Or, instead of =
saying =E2=80=9Cdeposit $2,000 to bet against Bitcoin using futures,=E2=80=
=9D you could say =E2=80=9Cdeposit $2,000 and we=E2=80=99ll lend you a Bitc=
oin to sell for dollars.=E2=80=9D Then the exchange probably=C2=A0would=C2=
=A0have some Bitcoins; certainly, the first customer=E2=80=99s account woul=
d show that she owned a Bitcoin. But it wouldn=E2=80=99t have that=C2=A0man=
y=C2=A0Bitcoins, because these trades would more or less offset: The exchan=
ge would borrow Bitcoins from the long customer to lend to the short custom=
er, and borrow dollars from the short customer to lend to the long one. Eco=
nomically this ends up looking quite a lot like the futures exchange, where=
 the core business is sitting between customers=E2=80=99 bets with each oth=
er rather than holding on to customers=E2=80=99 assets for them.
Fourth, and most important,=C2=A0this is really risky. This is not a busine=
ss of   taking customers=E2=80=99 money and holding onto it for them; this =
is=C2=A0a leveraged financial institution. If prices move too far in one di=
rection too quickly, some of your customers will owe you more money than th=
ey have in their accounts. If you are unable to collect from them =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0because they have gone bankrupt or otherwise =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you =
still owe money to the=C2=A0other=C2=A0customers who=C2=A0do=C2=A0have mone=
y in their accounts. If you don=E2=80=99t have enough to pay them, then you=
 go bankrupt and they don=E2=80=99t get paid.
II.
Here is how you manage the risks at a futures exchange:
=09You charge a lot of initial margin. When people make bets on your exchan=
ge, you make them put up a reasonable amount of money to make sure that the=
y=E2=80=99re good for it.=09You tailor the initial margin to the riskiness =
of the bets. If people are betting on very volatile and illiquid things, th=
ey have to put up more money than if they are betting on very stable and li=
quid things. You look at historical price moves to satisfy yourself that th=
e bets won=E2=80=99t move by more than the amount that customers have in th=
eir accounts.=09You might tailor the initial margin to the size of the bets=
. If people are making huge bets, they might have to put up more money=C2=
=A0per contract=C2=A0than if they are making small bets.=09You monitor vari=
ation margin carefully. If a position moves against a customer and she does=
n=E2=80=99t put up more money, you close out her bet quickly so that she ne=
ver ends up with a negative balance.=09You are careful about letting custom=
ers take money=C2=A0out. If some small illiquid token called MattCoin is tr=
ading at $1, and I take a long position on 10,000 MattCoin futures, posting=
 $1,000 of initial margin, and then 20 minutes later MattCoin trades up to =
$7, then I have $60,000 of gains and my account balance is $61,000. I might=
 call you up and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99d like to withdraw half of that=
 money.=E2=80=9D And you might say something like =E2=80=9Cmeh, no, let=E2=
=80=99s wait a while and see if this $7 price is for real.=E2=80=9D What yo=
u don=E2=80=99t want is for me to withdraw $30,000 and then have MattCoin d=
rop back to $1 immediately. Then you=E2=80=99d call me up and ask for the $=
30,000 back and I would probably have spent it. And now my account would ha=
ve a balance of negative $30,000, oops.

This is absolutely the core of the business; what a futures exchange=C2=A0i=
s=C2=A0is a business that manages these risks.=C2=A0And at a high level it =
is all very well-known stuff.
Take FTX, for instance, the crypto derivatives exchange founded by Sam Bank=
man-Fried; its=C2=A0name comes from the words =E2=80=9Cfutures exchange.=E2=
=80=9D Here is FTX=E2=80=99s help page  describing how it calculates margin=
 for futures contracts.=C2=A0The calculation is based on a margin factor th=
at is customized for each coin (depending on its volatility and liquidity) =
and the square root of position size. And here is  a Twitter thread that Ba=
nkman-Fried wrote in October, which I   discussed last week, about how FTX=
=E2=80=99s risk engine carefully takes into account position sizes and unus=
ual market moves, so that if you own a ton of one token that goes up a lot =
very rapidly, FTX will not let you take money out right away. FTX knew all =
of the things about how to manage the risks of a futures exchange, and desc=
ribed its risk management in thoughtful and sensible ways.
But while this is all well-known stuff, it is not=C2=A0easy. Sometimes pric=
es do move further and faster than you anticipated, and you have huge probl=
ems. We have talked a lot about the LME because   that=E2=80=99s what happe=
ned at the LME: Nickel prices shot up, traders who were short had negative =
balances, and there was just not enough money to pay out the traders who we=
re long. The LME solved this in a messy and unsatisfying way, basically shu=
tting down trading for a while and canceling some trades until prices went =
back down again. The traders who were long made money on paper, but then th=
e LME took it away from them, because risk-managing a futures exchange is h=
ard.
III.
Here is how you do fraud at a futures exchange:
=09You set up a futures exchange.=09You advertise, and also have, all of th=
e standard risk-management stuff, with thoughtful margining and liquidation=
. You make the exchange look=C2=A0safe.
=09You also do a lot of trades on the exchange with your own money.=09Witho=
ut telling anyone, you=C2=A0exempt=C2=A0yourself from all the risk-manageme=
nt stuff.=09If your bets move in your favor and your account gets bigger, y=
ou take the money out to spend on luxury condos or political campaign contr=
ibutions or venture capital.=09If your bets move against you and your accou=
nt gets smaller, or negative, you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0put more money ba=
ck in, and you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0close out your bets. You just let yo=
ur=C2=A0negative balance accrue and don=E2=80=99t worry about it.

In the long run, if you bet on volatile things, you will win some and lose =
some. But if you keep taking money out when you win, and=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0put money back in when you lose, then you=C2=A0will take out a lot of=
 actual money to spend on stuff, and your account=C2=A0at your own exchange=
=C2=A0will become very negative. If you win a billion dollars and take it o=
ut to spend, and then you lose it again and don=E2=80=99t put it back, then=
 on net nothing has happened (everybody=E2=80=99s bets are flat), but you h=
ave effectively transferred $1 billion of money from the exchange =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0ultimately, from=C2=A0other customers=C2=A0=E2=80=94 to yourself.=C2=
=A0
This is fraud for three reasons. First, in Step 2, you=C2=A0advertised=C2=
=A0that you had good risk management, but you had bad risk management. Agai=
n, the risk management is=C2=A0the whole business of a futures exchange; pe=
ople are putting their money at your exchange because they expect it will n=
ot disappear because you told them that you managed the risks, but you were=
 lying. You tricked customers into putting money at your exchange.
Second, it is fraud because it very predictably transfers money from your c=
ustomers to you. Again, if stuff goes up, you take money out; if it goes do=
wn, you don=E2=80=99t put money back in; in the long run stuff goes up and =
down, so you will extract money from the exchange. Once you have extracted =
enough money, there will not be enough left for the other customers. You tr=
icked customers into putting money at your exchange, and then you took it f=
or yourself.
Third, it=C2=A0could=C2=A0be fraud because you might be tempted to speed th=
e process along. You might say, well, look, if my account goes up I can tak=
e money out, and then if it goes down again I can ignore it, so I want stuf=
f that will go up and down rapidly. So you might find a MattCoin =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0a small illiquid token =E2=80=94=C2=A0to bet on, then pump up its pri=
ce so you can withdraw a=C2=A0lot of money, then walk away whistling as it =
collapses.
Or more to the point you can create your own token, sell a little of it int=
o the market to establish a market price, keep 97% of it for yourself, and =
make markets in the token to keep the market price up. Then you go to your =
own exchange and say =E2=80=9Chey I have billions and billions of dollars w=
orth of this token, can I borrow against it?=E2=80=9D And then the exchange=
 says =E2=80=9Csure, that seems fine,=E2=80=9D because (1) you=C2=A0run=C2=
=A0the exchange and (2) you have exempted yourself from any sort of thought=
ful risk management. =E2=80=9CYou own 97% of a token that really only you t=
rade, and you want to put up that token as collateral to borrow billions of=
 dollars of real money against its suspect market value? Sure, no problem,=
=E2=80=9D the exchange says to you, not because that is a sensible trade bu=
t because you are doing fraud.
One more point here. Eventually this collapses. Eventually your balance at =
your own exchange gets really negative, and customers try to withdraw their=
 money, and you don=E2=80=99t have enough to give to them, because you ende=
d up transferring too much of it to yourself and spending it. Customers not=
ice, there is a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank,=E2=80=9D and your exchange ends u=
p in bankruptcy.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s bad! But you have an excuse! The excuse is that you were a f=
utures exchange, a levered financial institution, and that is=C2=A0hard. Yo=
u made some mistakes, of risk management and credit extension. You should h=
ave liquidated some customers more quickly; you should have extended less c=
redit against their weird illiquid tokens. But these are not always easy ca=
lls, and sometimes even traditional futures exchanges mess it up. This wasn=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0fraud, you can say; it was just a series of=C2=A0mistakes.
In other words, this is a good way to do fraud because what looks like =E2=
=80=9Cstealing customer money for yourself=E2=80=9D can instead be characte=
rized as =E2=80=9Cmaking unfortunate mistakes in the complicated nuanced bu=
siness of extending leverage to certain customers.=E2=80=9D Those certain c=
ustomers are=C2=A0you, yes, but mistakes happen.
