X-affiliated tokens. The complaint further alleges that Bankman-Fried used =
commingled FTX customers=E2=80=99 funds at Alameda to make undisclosed vent=
ure investments, lavish real estate purchases, and large political donation=
s.
The allegations are that he stole customer money, but he didn=E2=80=99t tel=
l the shareholders about that as he was raising money from them, so really =
he stole their money too. So the SEC gets its piece of the action.=C2=A0
We talked last year about an everything-is-securities-fraud case against Go=
ldman Sachs Group Inc.; there, the allegations were=C2=A0that (1) Goldman d=
id some fraud while selling mortgage collateralized debt obligations, (2) i=
t didn=E2=80=99t tell shareholders that it was doing fraud while selling CD=
Os, so (3) it was doing fraud on the shareholders too.   I wrote:

As I often write, this theory can turn anything bad that a public company d=
oes into securities fraud: A company will put out some generic statements s=
aying that it is good, follows the law, has a code of ethics, etc.; then it=
 will turn out that the company secretly does bad things, breaks the law, h=
as unethical executives, etc.; the stock will drop (because the bad things =
are bad for the company); the shareholders will sue, saying =E2=80=9Cyou sa=
id you were good, we believed you, we bought the stock, but you were bad an=
d we lost money.=E2=80=9D And so=C2=A0climate change=C2=A0and=C2=A0sexual h=
arassment=C2=A0and=C2=A0lax customer data protections=C2=A0and=C2=A0mistrea=
tment of orcas=C2=A0can all be transmuted into securities fraud.=C2=A0
Here the underlying bad deed that was transmuted into securities fraud was=
=C2=A0also=C2=A0securities fraud=E2=80=94Goldman said it put customers firs=
t, then it=C2=A0did a fraud on the Abacus CDO buyers, then it got caught, t=
hen its stock dropped=E2=80=94but that is just a coincidence. If instead of=
 defrauding the Abacus CDO buyers Goldman had murdered them, that would not=
 have been securities fraud with respect to the Abacus CDO buyers (it would=
 have been murder), but it would still have been securities fraud with resp=
ect to Goldman=E2=80=99s shareholders (if the stock dropped after Goldman w=
as charged with murder).

Similarly, here, the underlying bad deed was (allegedly) running a fraud at=
 a crypto exchange, which certainly=C2=A0looks like securities fraud, but m=
ight not actually be.=C2=A0But it doesn=E2=80=99t matter; if you have share=
holders, any sort of fraud is also securities fraud.

