<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>I.</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is how you run a futures exchange:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You offer some bets on some propositi=
ons, say, whether Bitcoin will go up or down.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Some people come and take the long side of the bet (betting tha=
t Bitcoin will go up)=C2=A0and others take the short side (betting that it =
will go down).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In a sense, they ar=
e betting against each other, but they never meet and are not betting again=
st each other directly. Instead,=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94 the excha=
nge =E2=80=94=C2=A0are on the other side of all of their bets. You pay out =
the winners and collect from the losers. They all take your credit, not eac=
h other=E2=80=99s. The point of the exchange is to be a trustworthy central=
 counterparty for all the bets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Th=
ey all have to start by depositing some money in their accounts, so you can=
 be confident they=E2=80=99ll pay up on the bets. Let=E2=80=99s say the dep=
osit is $2,000 per Bitcoin bet, long or short.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> This is called =E2=80=9Cinitial margin.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">Each day,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0you check if Bitcoin went up or down.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">If it went up, you take some money out of the accounts of the=
 short bettors and put it into the accounts of the long bettors.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If it went down, you take some mo=
ney out of the accounts of the long bettors and put it into the accounts of=
 the short bettors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If a bettor=E2=
=80=99s account gets too low (because Bitcoin has moved against her), say b=
elow $1,000, you call her up and ask her to deposit more money.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This is called =E2=80=9Cvariation margin.=E2=80=9D If she doesn=
=E2=80=99t do it, you close out her bet at a loss.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">If a bettor=E2=80=99s account gets really high (because Bi=
tcoin has moved in her favor), she can withdraw some of the money in her ac=
count. If I bet on Bitcoin when it is at $17,000, depositing $2,000 of init=
ial margin, and it goes up to $30,000, then I have $15,000 in my account. (=
My initial $2,000 plus $13,000 of market moves.) You might let me withdraw,=
 say, $12,000 of it, leaving $3,000 in the account in case Bitcoin falls ag=
ain.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If a bettor=E2=80=99s account=
 ever gets=C2=A0<em>below=C2=A0</em>zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0if Bitcoin has move=
d so far against her so quickly that you didn=E2=80=99t have time to ask fo=
r more money or close out her bet, and now she owes more on the bet than sh=
e has in her account =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that=E2=80=99s bad. You still have=
 to pay out the winner on the bet, but you can=E2=80=99t collect from the l=
oser. (You can call and ask her for more money, but she might have made her=
self scarce.)=C2=A0You have to pay the winner out of your own =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the exchange=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0money. If you don=E2=80=99t have e=
nough money, then that=E2=80=99s really bad. Then you can=E2=80=99t pay out=
 all your customers on the amounts in their accounts.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to make a few points about this model. =
First, it is really common and traditional. There are lots of futures excha=
nges; we have, for reasons, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMzAvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1uaWNrZWwtbWFya2V0=
LWFsbW9zdC1icm9rZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWl=
sJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbm=
V5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6cefadf0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
