<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, notice that in this model there are no=
 Bitcoins at all. Some of your customers are long Bitcoin and some are shor=
t Bitcoin but you, the exchange, never have to have any Bitcoins. There are=
 no Bitcoins in the customers=E2=80=99 accounts, or in yours. You just sit =
in the middle of some bets between the customers. You hold onto some money =
for them =E2=80=94=C2=A0the amount they deposited as collateral for their b=
ets, customarily called =E2=80=9Cmargin=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you don=
=E2=80=99t keep the underlying=C2=A0<em>thing</em>, the Bitcoin that they a=
re betting on, in a safe.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You can trade nickel futures on the London Metals Exchange, but t=
he LME does not own any nickel.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, this model is at its core about offerin=
g=C2=A0<em>leveraged=C2=A0</em>trading on Bitcoins: It=E2=80=99s a way for =
people to bet on Bitcoin going up without paying the full $17,000-ish that =
you=E2=80=99d need to buy a Bitcoin, since they only have to put up $2,000 =
of margin in Step 4, which=C2=A0is less than $17,000. And it=E2=80=99s a wa=
y for people to bet on Bitcoin going down, which is a necessarily leveraged=
 trade: To bet against Bitcoin, you either need to borrow a Bitcoin and sel=
l it or do a futures trade; there is no simple unlevered way to just hold n=
egative one Bitcoin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so this model generalizes to doing margin =
trading on the actual underlying asset. Instead of saying =E2=80=9Cdeposit =
$2,000 to bet on Bitcoin using futures,=E2=80=9D you could say =E2=80=9Cdep=
osit $2,000 and=C2=A0we=E2=80=99ll lend you the other $15,000 to buy a Bitc=
oin.=E2=80=9D Or, instead of saying =E2=80=9Cdeposit $2,000 to bet against =
Bitcoin using futures,=E2=80=9D you could say =E2=80=9Cdeposit $2,000 and w=
e=E2=80=99ll lend you a Bitcoin to sell for dollars.=E2=80=9D Then the exch=
ange probably=C2=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em>have some Bitcoins; certainly, the f=
irst customer=E2=80=99s account would show that she owned a Bitcoin. But it=
 wouldn=E2=80=99t have that=C2=A0<em>many=C2=A0</em>Bitcoins, because these=
 trades would more or less offset: The exchange would borrow Bitcoins from =
the long customer to lend to the short customer, and borrow dollars from th=
e short customer to lend to the long one. Economically this ends up looking=
 quite a lot like the futures exchange, where the core business is sitting =
between customers=E2=80=99 bets with each other rather than holding on to c=
ustomers=E2=80=99 assets for them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fourth, and most important,=C2=A0<em>this is r=
eally risky</em>. This is not a business of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1k=
