#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  taking customers=E2=80=99 money and holding onto it for them</a>; this =
is=C2=A0a leveraged financial institution. If prices move too far in one di=
rection too quickly, some of your customers will owe you more money than th=
ey have in their accounts. If you are unable to collect from them =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0because they have gone bankrupt or otherwise =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you =
still owe money to the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>customers who=C2=A0<em>do=
=C2=A0</em>have money in their accounts. If you don=E2=80=99t have enough t=
o pay them, then you go bankrupt and they don=E2=80=99t get paid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>II.</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is how you manage the risks at a futures =
exchange:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You charge a lot of initial margin. W=
hen people make bets on your exchange, you make them put up a reasonable am=
ount of money to make sure that they=E2=80=99re good for it.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You tailor the initial margin to the riskiness o=
f the bets. If people are betting on very volatile and illiquid things, the=
y have to put up more money than if they are betting on very stable and liq=
uid things. You look at historical price moves to satisfy yourself that the=
 bets won=E2=80=99t move by more than the amount that customers have in the=
ir accounts.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You might tailor the =
initial margin to the size of the bets. If people are making huge bets, the=
y might have to put up more money=C2=A0<em>per contract=C2=A0</em>than if t=
hey are making small bets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You mon=
itor variation margin carefully. If a position moves against a customer and=
 she doesn=E2=80=99t put up more money, you close out her bet quickly so th=
at she never ends up with a negative balance.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">You are careful about letting customers take money=C2=A0<em>out=
</em>. If some small illiquid token called MattCoin is trading at $1, and I=
 take a long position on 10,000 MattCoin futures, posting $1,000 of initial=
 margin, and then 20 minutes later MattCoin trades up to $7, then I have $6=
0,000 of gains and my account balance is $61,000. I might call you up and s=
ay =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99d like to withdraw half of that money.=E2=80=9D A=
nd you might say something like =E2=80=9Cmeh, no, let=E2=80=99s wait a whil=
e and see if this $7 price is for real.=E2=80=9D What you don=E2=80=99t wan=
t is for me to withdraw $30,000 and then have MattCoin drop back to $1 imme=
diately. Then you=E2=80=99d call me up and ask for the $30,000 back and I w=
ould probably have spent it. And now my account would have a balance of neg=
ative $30,000, oops.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is absolutely the core of the business; w=
hat a futures exchange=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>is a business that manages the=
se risks.=C2=A0And at a high level it is all very well-known stuff.</p>
