ok it away from them, because risk-managing a futures exchange is hard.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>III.</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is how you do fraud at a futures exchange=
:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You set up a futures exchange.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You advertise, and also have, all of t=
he standard risk-management stuff, with thoughtful margining and liquidatio=
n. You make the exchange look=C2=A0<em>safe.</em>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You also do a lot of trades on th=
e exchange with your own money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wi=
thout telling anyone, you=C2=A0<em>exempt=C2=A0</em>yourself from all the r=
isk-management stuff.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If your bets=
 move in your favor and your account gets bigger, you take the money out to=
 spend on luxury condos or political campaign contributions or venture capi=
tal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If your bets move against you=
 and your account gets smaller, or negative, you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0</em>put more money back in, and you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>cl=
ose out your bets. You just let your=C2=A0negative balance accrue and don=
=E2=80=99t worry about it.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the long run, if you bet on volatile things=
, you will win some and lose some. But if you keep taking money out when yo=
u win, and=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>put money back in when you lose=
, then you=C2=A0will take out a lot of actual money to spend on stuff, and =
your account=C2=A0at your own exchange=C2=A0will become very negative. If y=
ou win a billion dollars and take it out to spend, and then you lose it aga=
in and don=E2=80=99t put it back, then on net nothing has happened (everybo=
dy=E2=80=99s bets are flat), but you have effectively transferred $1 billio=
n of money from the exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0ultimately, from=C2=A0<em>other=
 customers=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94 to yourself.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is fraud for three reasons. First, in Ste=
p 2, you=C2=A0<em>advertised=C2=A0</em>that you had good risk management, b=
ut you had bad risk management. Again, the risk management is=C2=A0<em>the =
whole business </em>of a futures exchange; people are putting their money a=
t your exchange because they expect it will not disappear because you told =
them that you managed the risks, but you were lying. You tricked customers =
into putting money at your exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, it is fraud because it very predictabl=
y transfers money from your customers to you. Again, if stuff goes up, you =
take money out; if it goes down, you don=E2=80=99t put money back in; in th=
e long run stuff goes up and down, so you will extract money from the excha=
nge. Once you have extracted enough money, there will not be enough left fo=
r the other customers. You tricked customers into putting money at your exc=
hange, and then you took it for yourself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, it=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>be fraud be=
cause you might be tempted to speed the process along. You might say, well,=
 look, if my account goes up I can take money out, and then if it goes down=
 again I can ignore it, so I want stuff that will go up and down rapidly. S=
o you might find a MattCoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0a small illiquid token =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0to bet on, then pump up its price so you can withdraw a=C2=A0lot of m=
oney, then walk away whistling as it collapses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or more to the point you can create your own t=
oken, sell a little of it into the market to establish a market price, keep=
 97% of it for yourself, and make markets in the token to keep the market p=
rice up. Then you go to your own exchange and say =E2=80=9Chey I have billi=
ons and billions of dollars worth of this token, can I borrow against it?=
=E2=80=9D And then the exchange says =E2=80=9Csure, that seems fine,=E2=80=
=9D because (1) you=C2=A0<em>run=C2=A0</em>the exchange and (2) you have ex=
empted yourself from any sort of thoughtful risk management. =E2=80=9CYou o=
wn 97% of a token that really only you trade, and you want to put up that t=
oken as collateral to borrow billions of dollars of real money against its =
suspect market value? Sure, no problem,=E2=80=9D the exchange says to you, =
not because that is a sensible trade but because you are doing fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One more point here. Eventually this collapses=
. Eventually your balance at your own exchange gets really negative, and cu=
stomers try to withdraw their money, and you don=E2=80=99t have enough to g=
ive to them, because you ended up transferring too much of it to yourself a=
nd spending it. Customers notice, there is a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank,=E2=
=80=9D and your exchange ends up in bankruptcy.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s bad! But you have an excuse! Th=
e excuse is that you were a futures exchange, a levered financial instituti=
on, and that is=C2=A0<em>hard</em>. You made some mistakes, of risk managem=
ent and credit extension. You should have liquidated some customers more qu=
ickly; you should have extended less credit against their weird illiquid to=
kens. But these are not always easy calls, and sometimes even traditional f=
utures exchanges mess it up. This wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>fraud</em>, you c=
an say; it was just a series of=C2=A0<em>mistakes</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words, this is a good way to do fraud=
 because what looks like =E2=80=9Cstealing customer money for yourself=E2=
=80=9D can instead be characterized as =E2=80=9Cmaking unfortunate mistakes=
 in the complicated nuanced business of extending leverage to certain custo=
mers.=E2=80=9D Those certain customers are=C2=A0<em>you</em>, yes, but mist=
akes happen.</p>
