om/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcn=
MvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JNWVhiQndOTjJrby92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB82aab712"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> Commodity Futures Trading Commission</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a lot going on here, but I want to fo=
cus on the simple story I laid out above. FTX was mainly a crypto futures e=
xchange. The CFTC says:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX offered trading in a large var=
iety of digital assets, including digital commodities such as bitcoin, ethe=
r, tether, and others. FTX operated primarily as a derivatives exchange and=
 offered trading in various types of options, futures, swaps, perpetual swa=
ps, and other digital commodity derivative products. FTX allowed customers =
to place buy (long) and sell (short) orders in an electronic order book, an=
d matched customer orders via its =E2=80=9Ctrading engine=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9Cmatching engine.=E2=80=9D FTX also offered a number of additional ser=
vices related to the trading of digital asset products. For example, FTX op=
erated a peer-to-peer (P2P) margin lending program where customers could of=
fer margined and leveraged offerings to one another.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And like any serious futures exchange it adver=
tised, and had, a sophisticated risk-management system. The SEC says:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In addition to generally promoting=
 the benefits of automated risk engines, Bankman-Fried repeatedly claimed t=
hat FTX=E2=80=99s own risk engine was especially sophisticated and carefull=
y calibrated. In a submission to the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, =
FTX touted its automated system, claiming that it calculated a customer=E2=
=80=99s margin level every 30 seconds; and that if the collateral on deposi=
t fell below the required margin level, FTX=E2=80=99s automated system woul=
d sell the customer=E2=80=99s portfolio assets until the collateral on depo=
sit exceeded the required margin level.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile though Alameda =E2=80=94=C2=A0which =
was co-founded and 90% owned by Bankman-Fried =E2=80=94=C2=A0was trading on=
 FTX and exempted from all of this. The CFTC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda was exempt from FTX=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Cauto-liquidation=E2=80=9D risk engine functions, which would automatical=
ly liquidate (sell) a customer=E2=80=99s open position when their =E2=80=9C=
Maintenance Margin Fraction=E2=80=9D fell below a certain determined level.=
 All customers who took on too much leverage or risk on FTX would thus be a=
uto-liquidated by the exchange. Alameda was exempt from this=E2=80=94it cou=
ld not be liquidated on FTX Trading under any conditions. This exception wa=
s hard coded into FTX=E2=80=99s system. This advantage was not publicly dis=
closed during the Relevant Period. The existence of this and other advantag=
es directly contradicted public statements made by and on behalf of Defenda=
nts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda=E2=80=99s account on FTX also had a sp=
ecial designation in the FTX Trading code, labeled as an =E2=80=9Callow neg=
ative flag,=E2=80=9D which allowed Alameda to execute a transaction even if=
 it did not have the funds available in its account to do so. Alameda also =
had an essentially unbounded=C2=A0credit limit in the FTX database. On at l=
east one occasion during the Relevant Period, Alameda had reached a previou=
sly-set borrowing limit for its FTX account. In response, Bankman-Fried dir=
ected FTX personnel to raise the borrowing limit to a level that would be u=
nlikely to ever be exceeded. On information and belief, FTX personnel ultim=
ately raised Alameda=E2=80=99s borrowing limit to be many tens of billions =
of dollars. Alameda=E2=80=99s borrowed funds could also be withdrawn from F=
TX. These features, in combination, allowed Alameda unlimited ability to bo=
rrow and withdraw and digital assets directly from FTX Trading to put towar=
ds its off-platform activities.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the SEC adds:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of these special privileges we=
re afforded to Alameda=E2=80=94and only Alameda=E2=80=94at Bankman-Fried=E2=
=80=99s direction, and all were hidden from investors. These privileges per=
mitted Alameda to draw on FTX customer assets to a virtually unlimited exte=
nt for its own uses. Because its own FTX trading account was able to mainta=
in a negative balance of billions of dollars, unbacked by sufficient collat=
eral, Alameda was able to divert billions of dollars in FTX customer assets=
. Alameda did just that in 2022.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much of this money went to pay off Alameda=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>lenders: Alameda was a trading firm that m=
ade risky bets, some of those bets lost, and it owed money to lenders; it p=
aid them with money it withdrew from FTX. Some of it, though, went to =E2=
=80=9Cpay hundreds of millions of dollars in =E2=80=98loans=E2=80=99 to Ban=
kman-Fried and other FTX executives, as well as hundreds of millions more t=
o fund additional venture investments.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, as we have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS=
1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjJfTU9ORVlTV=
FVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEy=
MTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC836655c2" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  discussed</a> a few <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMT=
MyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0b=
V90ZXJtPTIyMTIxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
0dc6579d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  times</a>, Alameda borrowed huge amounts of money secur=
ed by rickety FTX-created tokens like FTT and Serum, tokens that Alameda ow=
ned most of and whose market price was mostly set by Alameda. =E2=80=9CThe =
collateral Alameda deposited on FTX consisted largely of illiquid, FTX-affi=
liated tokens, including FTT,=E2=80=9D says the SEC. And the CFTC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of Alameda=E2=80=99s most significant hold=
ings was the FTT digital asset. FTT was the FTX =E2=80=9Cexchange token=E2=
=80=9D and could be used to obtain discounted trading fees for transactions=
 on FTX Trading. On information and belief, Alameda did not pay to acquire =
its FTT holdings. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda=E2=80=99s FTT holdings were a signific=
ant portion of its balance sheet and a significant portion of all FTT in ci=
rculation. Alameda valued its FTT holdings on its balance sheet at the mark=
et price at which FTT was traded, without applying any discount to reflect =
that it could not have sold its significant FTT holdings into the marketpla=
ce without causing a sharp reduction in its trading price. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda relied on its significant holdings of =
FTT and similar illiquid tokens, valued at the market value of the asset wi=
thout discount, as collateral to support a number of large loans from vario=
us digital asset lending platforms. During the Relevant Period, Alameda too=
k out a large number loans, at times totaling as much as $10 billion in not=
ional value during the Relevant Period.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eventually the market got concerned about FTT =
and those third-party lenders called in their loans to Alameda, so:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In approximately May and/or June 2=
022, Alameda was subject to a large number of such margin calls and loan re=
calls. It did not have sufficient liquid assets to service its loans. Inste=
ad, at the direction of Bankman-Fried, Alameda greatly increased its usage =
of FTX customer funds to meet its external debt obligations. Alameda was ab=
le to rely on its undisclosed ordinary-course access to FTX credit and cust=
omer funds to facilitate these large withdrawals, which were several billio=
n dollars in notional value.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyY=
WwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVk=
aXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXB=
haWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD836655c2" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  have assu=
med</a> that Alameda ended up borrowing billions of dollars from FTX=C2=A0<=
em>secured by=C2=A0</em>its illiquid weird FTX-affiliated tokens like FTT, =
and today=E2=80=99s charges sort of suggest that but aren=E2=80=99t clear. =
Instead, Alameda seems to have borrowed billions of dollars from=C2=A0<em>o=
ther lenders=C2=A0</em>secured by those weird tokens (which is weird!), and=
 then when those lenders got nervous Alameda paid them back with money that=
 it borrowed from FTX. Since it could more or less do that unsecured =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it could just have a negative account balance! =E2=80=94 it doesn=
=E2=80=99t matter very much whether it put up the FTT tokens as collateral.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, there was also a bizarre, enormous, u=
nsecured,=C2=A0<em>no-interest=C2=A0</em>loan that FTX made to Alameda and =
documented as basically an accounting glitch. The SEC:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the start of FTX=E2=80=99s operations in =
or around May 2019 until at least 2021, FTX customers deposited fiat curren=
cy (e.g., U.S. Dollars) into bank accounts controlled by Alameda. Billions =
of dollars of FTX customer funds were so deposited into Alameda-controlled =
bank accounts. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda did not segregate these customer funds=
, but instead commingled them with its other assets, and used them indiscri=
minately to fund its trading operations and Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s other v=
entures.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This multi-billion-dollar liability was reflec=
ted in an internal account in the FTX database that was not tied to Alameda=
 but was instead called =E2=80=9Cfiat@ftx.com.=E2=80=9D Characterizing the =
amount of customer funds sent to Alameda as an internal FTX account had the=
 effect of concealing Alameda=E2=80=99s liability in FTX=E2=80=99s internal=
 systems.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically if you deposited $100 at FTX through=
 Alameda, then (1) Alameda kept the $100 to use for its own purposes, (2) F=
TX credited $100 to your account and (3) FTX recorded an offsetting $100 lo=
an to Alameda. But =E2=80=9Ccharacterizing the amount of customer funds sen=
t to Alameda as an internal FTX account had the effect of concealing Alamed=
a=E2=80=99s liability in FTX=E2=80=99s internal systems=E2=80=9D: It was <e=
m>sort of=C2=A0</em>recorded as a loan, but not for purposes of FTX=E2=80=
=99s risk-management systems. (It was not so much recorded as a loan as it =
was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.25852=
7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZ=
nR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0=
bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIxMyZ1dG1=
fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC0dc6579d" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  re=
corded as a</a> =E2=80=9Chidden, poorly internally labled =E2=80=98fiat@=E2=
=80=99 account,=E2=80=9D in Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s own words.) And =E2=80=
=9CAlameda was not required to pay interest on the liability reflected in t=
he =E2=80=98fiat@ftx.com=E2=80=99 account.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The alleged fraud here is mostly these sorts o=
f things: having a system that funneled money from customers to Alameda, in=
 the form of a limitless line of credit and exemption from liquidation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But =E2=80=94=C2=A0as we have also <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDEvc2JmLW1pc3NlZC1m=
dHgtcy1yaXNrcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV=
0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3=
R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7c4e0e26" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  discussed</a> <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDYveW91LWNhbi10=
LXRlbGwtYW5hbHlzdHMtdG9vLW11Y2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21=
lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjEzJnV0bV9jYW=
1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC273288e9" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  before<=
/a> =E2=80=94 another important element of the alleged fraud is that FTX=C2=
=A0<em>advertised=C2=A0</em>good risk management and=C2=A0<em>had=C2=A0</em=
>bad risk management. Bankman-Fried has been going around on a weird media =
tour whose essential message is =E2=80=9CI made mistakes and was careless, =
sorry,=E2=80=9D presumably thinking that that is a=C2=A0<em>defense=C2=A0</=
em>to fraud charges, that =E2=80=9Ccarelessness=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cfraud=
=E2=80=9D are entirely separate categories.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The SEC is having none of it:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried repeatedly touted FTX=E2=80=99s =
automated risk mitigation protocols=E2=80=94 which he called FTX=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Crisk engine=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94to the public, and prospective invest=
ors, as a safe and reliable way for crypto asset trading platforms to manag=
e risk. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0In addition to generally promoting the benefits of a=
utomated risk engines, Bankman-Fried repeatedly claimed that FTX=E2=80=99s =
own risk engine was especially sophisticated and carefully calibrated. ...<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried thus misled FTX=E2=80=99s invest=
ors by representing that its risk engine would protect FTX customer funds a=
nd would limit FTX=E2=80=99s exposure to any single customer, while failing=
 to disclose that Bankman-Fried had personally directed that the engine not=
 apply to one of its largest customers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Bankman-Fried acknowledged in a network tel=
evision interview on or about December 1, 2022: =E2=80=9CI wasn=E2=80=99t e=
ven trying, like, I wasn=E2=80=99t spending any time or effort trying to ma=
nage risk on FTX.=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried continued: =E2=80=9CWhat happened,=
 happened=E2=80=94and, if I had been spending an hour a day thinking about =
risk management on FTX, I don=E2=80=99t think that would have happened.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you attract customers and investors by sayi=
ng that you have good risk management, and then you lose their money, and t=
hen you say =E2=80=9Coh sorry we had bad risk management,=E2=80=9D that is =
not a defense against fraud charges! That is a confession!</p>
