<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Everything is securities fraud</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way! If you run a crypto=C2=A0exchange,=
 and you steal your customers=E2=80=99 money, is that securities fraud? Tha=
t is a hard question. I think that the US Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDgvZ2F=
yeS1nZW5zbGVyLXdhbnRzLXRvLXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNyeXB0bz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjJfTU9ORV=
lTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yM=
jEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4b3f3bd9" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  would mostly say</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most crypto tokens are securities,</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You did a fraud about the tokens,</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So=C2=A0you did securities fraud.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that interpretation is not free from doubt=
. Some crypto tokens (Bitcoin, etc.) are clearly=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>sec=
urities, and with the rest it is debatable; the SEC has to fight over this =
interpretation in court. Going after a crypto exchange for securities fraud=
 for stealing its customers=E2=80=99 money is, legally, a stretch for the S=
EC. The Department of Justice can go after the exchange for=C2=A0<em>wire f=
raud</em>, and the CFTC can go after a crypto futures exchange for commodit=
y futures fraud, but the SEC might feel a bit left out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unless the crypto exchange sold=C2=A0<em>stock=
</em>. If the crypto exchange raised money from=C2=A0<em>investors</em>=C2=
=A0by selling them=C2=A0<em>stock</em>, well, the stock is clearly a securi=
ty. And if it didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>the investors, as it s=
old them the stock, =E2=80=9Chey by the way we are stealing money from our =
customers,=E2=80=9D then the investors were defrauded.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is the theory that we talk about all the =
time around here, that =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D If=
 a company does a bad thing, and it didn=E2=80=99t tell its shareholders ab=
out it, then it deceived the shareholders and that=E2=80=99s fraud. Ordinar=
ily this theory applies only to=C2=A0<em>public=C2=A0</em>companies, but if=
 you=E2=80=99re a high-profile enough private company and you raised a lot =
of money from outside investors while doing bad stuff and not telling them =
about it, then I guess that=E2=80=99s good enough.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzL=
XJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0yMTk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc036bd37" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the SEC=
=E2=80=99s case</a> against Bankman-Fried is a little silly because, althou=
gh he allegedly defrauded=C2=A0<em>customers=C2=A0</em>out of billions of d=
ollars, the SEC is vindicating the rights of the=C2=A0<em>venture capitalis=
ts=C2=A0</em>who supported him:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s com=
plaint, since at least May 2019, FTX, based in The Bahamas, raised more tha=
n $1.8 billion from equity investors, including approximately $1.1 billion =
from approximately 90 U.S.-based investors. In his representations to inves=
tors, Bankman-Fried promoted FTX as a safe, responsible crypto asset tradin=
g platform, specifically touting FTX=E2=80=99s sophisticated, automated ris=
k measures to protect customer assets. The complaint alleges that, in reali=
ty, Bankman-Fried orchestrated a years-long fraud to conceal from FTX=E2=80=
=99s investors (1) the undisclosed diversion of FTX customers=E2=80=99 fund=
s to Alameda Research LLC, his privately-held crypto hedge fund; (2) the un=
disclosed special treatment afforded to Alameda on the FTX platform, includ=
ing providing Alameda with a virtually unlimited =E2=80=9Cline of credit=E2=
=80=9D funded by the platform=E2=80=99s customers and exempting Alameda fro=
m certain key FTX risk mitigation measures; and (3) undisclosed risk stemmi=
ng from FTX=E2=80=99s exposure to Alameda=E2=80=99s significant holdings of=
 overvalued, illiquid assets such as FTX-affiliated tokens. The complaint f=
urther alleges that Bankman-Fried used commingled FTX customers=E2=80=99 fu=
nds at Alameda to make undisclosed venture investments, lavish real estate =
purchases, and large political donations.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The allegations are that he stole customer mon=
ey, but he didn=E2=80=99t tell the shareholders about that as he was raisin=
g money from them, so really he stole their money too. So the SEC gets its =
piece of the action.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked last year about an everything-is-sec=
urities-fraud case against Goldman Sachs Group Inc.; there, the allegations=
 were=C2=A0that (1) Goldman did some fraud while selling mortgage collatera=
lized debt obligations, (2) it didn=E2=80=99t tell shareholders that it was=
 doing fraud while selling CDOs, so (3) it was doing fraud on the sharehold=
ers too. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.=
258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDIt=
MDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9=
uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW=
09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ=
249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfa17675e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As I often write, this theory can turn anythin=
g bad that a public company does into securities fraud: A company will put =
out some generic statements saying that it is good, follows the law, has a =
code of ethics, etc.; then it will turn out that the company secretly does =
bad things, breaks the law, has unethical executives, etc.; the stock will =
drop (because the bad things are bad for the company); the shareholders wil=
l sue, saying =E2=80=9Cyou said you were good, we believed you, we bought t=
he stock, but you were bad and we lost money.=E2=80=9D And so=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTAtMjUvZXh4b24taXMt=
aW4tdHJvdWJsZS1vdmVyLWNsaW1hdGUtY2hhbmdlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZ=
GJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIxMy=
Z1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35fbb3dd" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">climate change</a>=C2=A0and=C2=A0<a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDUtMDEvaXQtZG9lc24tdC1wY=
XktdG8tYmUtdG9vLWV0aGljYWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1=
bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWl=
nbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4fcd0e9f" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">sexual harassment</a>=C2=A0and=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29972411.258527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
